var questions_youtube_guru6 = [{"id":"yt-guru6-1","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A husband and wife have combined earnings of greater than $300,000 in each of the last two years. If it's reasonably expected that this level of income will remain the same, the couple is considered:","choices":{"A":"A qualified investor","B":"An accredited investor","C":"An institutional investor","D":"A qualified institutional buyer (QIB)"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “An accredited investor.” An accredited investor includes individuals with income over $200,000 ($300,000 joint) in each of the prior two years and a reasonable expectation of the same this year.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-2","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"ABC Corporation's Quarterly Dividend — Dividend: $0.15, Declaration Date: 3rd, Ex-dividend Date: 28th, Record Date: 28th, Payment Date: 31st. Based on the information above, if a customer purchased 1,000 shares on the 28th, what's the cash amount of dividends she receives?","choices":{"A":"$15,000","B":"$1,500","C":"$150","D":"$0"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “$0.” Buying on the ex-dividend date means the buyer is not entitled to the dividend; she receives $0.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-3","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"All of the following statements concerning hedge funds are TRUE, EXCEPT the funds:","choices":{"A":"May engage in short selling","B":"Must register under the Investment Company Act of 1940 if offered to U.S. residents","C":"May borrow funds in an attempt to boost returns","D":"May concentrate assets in a few positions"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “Must register under the Investment Company Act of 1940 if offered to U.S. residents.” Hedge funds are exempt from the Investment Company Act of 1940 (they rely on private-offering exemptions), so they need not register.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-4","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A company's stock has decreased in value as a result of increased costs associated with impending regulations. This is considered:","choices":{"A":"Liquidity risk","B":"Credit risk","C":"Political risk","D":"Default risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “Political risk.” New regulations raising a company's costs reflect political/regulatory risk, not credit or default risk.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-5","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"An investor has a portfolio in which 25% is invested in an oil company, 35% is invested in a pharmaceutical stock, 30% is invested in an exchange-traded fund that tracks the S&P 500 Index, and the final 10% is invested in money-market funds. Which of the following risks is inherent in the portfolio?","choices":{"A":"Non-systematic","B":"Political","C":"Credit","D":"Liquidity"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Non-systematic.” The portfolio's risk comes from company/industry concentration (oil, pharma), which is diversifiable non-systematic risk.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-6","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The investments in a Coverdell Education Savings Account (CESA) are:","choices":{"A":"Determined by the investor","B":"Determined by the firm through which it's opened","C":"Limited to AAA rated bonds","D":"Limited to mutual funds"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Determined by the investor.” A Coverdell ESA's investments are chosen by the account owner; the contributor decides how the funds are invested.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-7","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following has the most interest-rate risk?","choices":{"A":"A 30-year premium bond","B":"A 30-year zero coupon bond","C":"A 10-year premium bond","D":"A 10-year zero coupon bond"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “A 30-year zero coupon bond.” Zero-coupon bonds have the longest duration; a 30-year zero has the greatest interest-rate (duration) risk of the choices.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-8","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"When do option trades settle?","choices":{"A":"T + 1","B":"T + 3","C":"T + 4","D":"At expiration"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “T + 1.” Listed equity option trades settle on the next business day, T+1.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-10","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"All of the following characteristics would be associated with a growth company, EXCEPT that it has a:","choices":{"A":"High price/earnings ratio","B":"High dividend payout ratio","C":"High amount of research and development costs","D":"Wide trading range for the price of its stock"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “High dividend payout ratio.” Growth companies retain earnings to fund expansion, so they have low (not high) dividend payout ratios.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-11","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"In which of the following funds is the percentage that's invested in each of the various asset categories adjusted as financial markets change?","choices":{"A":"An asset allocation fund","B":"An S&P 500 index fund","C":"A bond index fund","D":"A growth fund"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “An asset allocation fund.” An asset allocation fund shifts its percentages among asset classes as market conditions change, managed by the adviser.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-12","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"A 529A or ABLE account is permitted for which of the following persons?","choices":{"A":"A person who is receiving retirement benefits","B":"A person who is saving for college","C":"A person who has a significant disability","D":"A person who is a minor"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “A person who has a significant disability.” An ABLE account is for individuals with significant disabilities; a 529 plan is for education savings.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-13","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"A registered employee is required to disclose which of the following activities to her employing broker-dealer?","choices":{"A":"Volunteering for a local charity every Thursday night.","B":"Serving as a director for a profit-based firm.","C":"Volunteering for a local charity on a one-time basis.","D":"Playing basketball in a city-wide tournament."},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “Serving as a director for a profit-based firm.” Registered persons must disclose outside business activities such as serving as a director of a for-profit firm to their employer.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-14","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Jamie has inherited 500 shares of an investment company. She calls her broker to redeem the shares and is informed that the kind of investment company she owns makes no provision for future purchases or redemptions. What kind of investment company does she own?","choices":{"A":"An open-end fund","B":"A closed-end fund","C":"A unit investment trust","D":"A face-amount certificate company"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “A closed-end fund.” Closed-end funds make a fixed offering and provide no ongoing redemption mechanism; the investor must sell in the market.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-15","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A company has $50,000,000 par value convertible bonds outstanding. The coupon rate is 8%. The bonds are currently selling at 96. What is the current yield?","choices":{"A":"7.0%","B":"7.5%","C":"8.0%","D":"8.3%"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “8.3%.” Current yield is annual interest divided by price: (8% x $1,000) / ($960) = $80 / $960 = 8.33%.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-16","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"What tax advantage is available with a real estate investments trust (REIT) investment?","choices":{"A":"Distributions are taxed at the same 20% rate as corporate dividends.","B":"Everything an investor receives is taxed at the preferential long-term capital gains rate.","C":"All of the income is taxed at the corporate tax rate which is often lower than the highest tax rate assessed on an individual's ordinary income.","D":"If 90% of the income is distributed, only the shareholders pay taxes, thereby avoiding corporate taxes."},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “If 90% of the income is distributed, only the shareholders pay taxes, thereby avoiding corporate taxes.” REITs avoid double taxation by distributing at least 90% of income; shareholders pay tax, the REIT is not taxed at the entity level.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-17","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"A Treasury bond is quoted 105.04 - 105.24. The purchase price that a customer would expect to pay would be:","choices":{"A":"$1,051.25","B":"$1,052.40","C":"$1,054.00","D":"$1,057.50"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “$1,057.50.” A customer buying pays the ask; 105.24 equals 105 and 24/32 = $1,057.50 per $1,000 face.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-18","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"A registered representative has recently passed the Series 7 Examination. If the RR conducts business in five states, she is required to:","choices":{"A":"Register in three of the five states","B":"Notify FINRA, but not required to register in any of the states","C":"Register in the states in which she has an office","D":"Register in all five states"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Register in all five states.” An agent must register (be licensed) in every state where she has an office and conducts business - here all five states.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-19","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"An investor shifted the allocation of corporate bonds in his portfolio to foreign equities. As a result, he will be more exposed to:","choices":{"A":"Political risk","B":"Liquidity risk","C":"Prepayment risk","D":"Interest-rate risk"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Political risk.” Foreign equities add exposure to foreign governments and currencies, i.e., political risk not present in domestic corporates.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-20","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Which of the following is found in a preliminary prospectus?","choices":{"A":"The effective date","B":"The public offering price (POP)","C":"A fee table","D":"The number of shares being issued"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “The number of shares being issued.” The preliminary prospectus (red herring) states the number of shares to be issued but not the final POP or effective date.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-21","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A company has announced a tender offer for its shares at $50. The issuer wants to purchase a minimum of 100,000 shares, up to a maximum of 1,000,000 shares. If 80,000 shares are tendered, how much will an investor receive if he has tendered 1,000 shares?","choices":{"A":"$0","B":"$50,000","C":"$40,000","D":"$4,000"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “$0.” A partial tender below the minimum fails; if fewer than the 100,000 minimum are tendered, no shares are purchased, so the investor gets $0.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-22","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Who creates the Options Disclosure Document?","choices":{"A":"The SEC","B":"The OCC","C":"Each broker-dealer","D":"FINRA"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “The OCC.” The Options Clearing Corporation (OCC) issues the Options Disclosure Document (ODD).","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-23","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"When is an underwriting broker-dealer able to accept payment from an investor for the purchase of a new issue?","choices":{"A":"When the registration is declared effective.","B":"After the delivery of the red herring.","C":"When the preliminary prospectus is amended.","D":"Only if the transaction takes place during the cooling-off period."},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “When the registration is declared effective.” Payment for a new issue may be accepted only after the registration statement is declared effective by the SEC.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-24","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"When is a dividend payment made?","choices":{"A":"On the payment date","B":"On the record date","C":"On the ex-dividend date","D":"On the declaration date"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “On the payment date.” Dividends are actually paid on the payment date, distinct from the record, ex-dividend, and declaration dates.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-25","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"If a market maker has a current quote of 50.00 - 50.05 (15 x 20), this indicates that the firm is willing to:","choices":{"A":"Sell 200 shares at $50.00 and buy 150 shares at $50.05","B":"Buy 150 shares at $50.00 and sell 200 shares at $50.05","C":"Sell 1,500 shares at $50.00 and buy 2,000 shares at $50.05","D":"Buy 1,500 shares at $50.00 and sell 2,000 shares at $50.05"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Buy 1,500 shares at $50.00 and sell 2,000 shares at $50.05.” In a quote, the market maker buys at the bid (50.00) and sells at the ask (50.05); (15x20) means 15x100=1,500 to buy and 20x100=2,000 to sell.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-26","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"If a customer purchases securities and fails to pay for them by the payment date, the brokerage firm will:","choices":{"A":"Sell out the securities and freeze the account","B":"Notify the Federal Reserve Board","C":"Notify the SEC","D":"Close the customer's account for a specified period"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Sell out the securities and freeze the account.” If a customer fails to pay, the firm sells out the position and freezes the account for 90 days.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-27","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The main difference between closed-end and open-end investment companies is that closed-end investment companies:","choices":{"A":"Have shares that are not permitted to be purchased on margin","B":"Offer a fixed number of shares","C":"Continually issue and redeem their shares","D":"Determine their share prices once per day"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “Offer a fixed number of shares.” Closed-end funds issue a fixed number of shares in a one-time IPO and then trade on an exchange; open-end funds continually issue/redeem.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-28","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"A broker-dealer is acting as a distribution participant in a public offering of stock. To entice customer purchases, the firm pledges to repurchase shares sold in the offering from its customers at a price that's higher than the original public offering price (POP). This type of pledge is:","choices":{"A":"Prohibited unless the customers are free to sell the securities into the open market","B":"Allowed if the firm immediately sets aside funds for the repurchase","C":"Allowed if the customers' securities and cash are deposited into escrow","D":"Prohibited, fraudulent, and manipulative"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Prohibited, fraudulent, and manipulative.” Pledging to repurchase shares above the POP is a prohibited, fraudulent, and manipulative practice (a form of market manipulation).","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-29","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"If a company is utilizing statutory voting, how many votes will a common shareholder receive per vacant seat on the board?","choices":{"A":"One vote for each vacant position on the board","B":"One vote for each director that's present at the meeting","C":"One vote for each share that the stockholder owns","D":"One for each proxy that's filed by the board of directors"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “One vote for each share that the stockholder owns.” Under statutory voting, each share gets one vote per director seat, so the shareholder votes one vote per share for each vacancy.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-30","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A U.S. government bond is selling in the market at 95.28. The dollar value of this bond is:","choices":{"A":"$950.87","B":"$952.80","C":"$9,587.50","D":"$958.75"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “$958.75.” Government bonds are quoted in 32nds; 95.28 = 95 + 28/32 = 95.875% of $1,000 = $958.75.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-31","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A 5% $1,000 par value bond sells at $900 and matures in 10 years. What is the amount of each interest payment?","choices":{"A":"$25","B":"$45","C":"$50","D":"$90"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “$25.” Each semiannual interest payment is (5% x $1,000)/2 = $25.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-32","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The current market value of a stock is below the strike price of a call option. This situation is referred to as:","choices":{"A":"At-the-money","B":"In-the-money","C":"Out-of-the-money","D":"Behind-the-money"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “Out-of-the-money.” A call is out-of-the-money when the stock price is below the strike price.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-33","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding Form 10-K?","choices":{"A":"It must be filed at the end of an issuer's fiscal quarter.","B":"It contains voting information and must be sent to shareholders before a corporate election.","C":"It must be filed at the end of an issuer's fiscal year.","D":"It must be offered to shareholders on a monthly basis."},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “It must be filed at the end of an issuer's fiscal year.” Form 10-K is the annual (fiscal year-end) report; Form 10-Q is the quarterly report.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-34","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A unit investment trust (UIT):","choices":{"A":"Will typically have 12b-1 fees","B":"Represents an undivided interest in a fixed account","C":"Represents a dividend interest in a fixed account","D":"Will typically assess a back-end load"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “Represents an undivided interest in a fixed account.” A UIT represents an undivided interest in a fixed, unmanaged portfolio of securities.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-35","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Which of the following may NOT occur during the waiting period of the securities registration process?","choices":{"A":"The underwriter publishes a tombstone ad","B":"An underwriter sends a red herring to a potential customer","C":"An RR accepts a cash deposit for the offering from an interested customer","D":"An RR discusses the offering with a customer over the phone"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “An RR accepts a cash deposit for the offering from an interested customer.” During the waiting/cooling-off period, an RR may not accept money or orders; tombstones, red herrings, and discussions are permitted.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-37","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"What's the maximum profit for the buyer of a call option?","choices":{"A":"The premium","B":"The strike price","C":"The strike price minus the premium","D":"Unlimited"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Unlimited.” The buyer of a call has unlimited upside as the underlying can rise without limit; loss is limited to the premium paid.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-38","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The main disadvantage of §529 Prepaid Tuition Plans compared to §529 Savings Plans is that:","choices":{"A":"Distributions that are not used to pay for educational expenses are subject to a 10% tax penalty","B":"Qualified distributions may be used to pay for tuition, books, room and board, and other expenses","C":"The account owner may lose financially if the student does not attend a public school in that state","D":"The account owner can lock-in the beneficiary's tuition at a state college at a reduced rate"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “The account owner may lose financially if the student does not attend a public school in that state.” Prepaid tuition plans lock in in-state public tuition, so the owner loses if the beneficiary attends a private or out-of-state school.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-39","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"Obtaining best execution includes all the following factors, EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Price and volatility","B":"The general character of the market","C":"The size and type of transaction","D":"The number of market makers for the security"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “The number of market makers for the security.” Best execution factors include price, volatility, size/type, and market character; the number of market makers is not a listed factor.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-40","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A variable annuity contract holder dies during the accumulation period. Which of the following is TRUE regarding the tax consequences?","choices":{"A":"All proceeds are considered a return of capital.","B":"The growth is taxable as a capital gain to the beneficiary.","C":"Proceeds in excess of cost are taxable as ordinary income to the beneficiary.","D":"The growth above cost is not taxable if the beneficiary rolls it over into a retirement plan."},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “Proceeds in excess of cost are taxable as ordinary income to the beneficiary.” On death during accumulation, the beneficiary receives the contract value; amounts above cost basis are taxed as ordinary income.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-41","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"A broker-dealer must establish information barriers between which two departments?","choices":{"A":"Research and compliance","B":"Institutional trading and retail trading","C":"Investment banking and compliance","D":"Investment banking and trading"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Investment banking and trading.” Information barriers (Chinese walls) separate investment banking from the trading desk to prevent misuse of material nonpublic information.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-42","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Government-sponsored enterprise securities are comparable to direct government obligations with regard to all of the following statements, EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"They trade in the over-the-counter market","B":"All are government guaranteed","C":"Short-term securities are quoted on a discount yield","D":"Long-term securities are quoted as a percentage of par"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “All are government guaranteed.” GSE securities (Fannie, Freddie) are NOT direct U.S. government obligations and are not guaranteed by the U.S. government.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-43","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"An investor purchases a 20-year 5.30% bond at par value that will yield 5.75% if called at the first call date in five years. The yield to maturity on the bond is:","choices":{"A":"5.30%","B":"More than 5.30%","C":"Between 5.30% and 5.75%","D":"5.75%"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “5.30%.” At issuance the coupon equals the YTM; since the bond sells at par, YTM = 5.30%.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-44","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which of the following statements is NOT TRUE about a fidelity bond?","choices":{"A":"It protects customers in the event their broker-dealer goes bankrupt.","B":"It's insurance that protects a broker-dealer in case of fraud such as forgery or counterfeit currency.","C":"FINRA must be notified if the bond is cancelled or substantially modified.","D":"It covers securities that are held at the brokerage firm as well as those in transit."},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “It protects customers in the event their broker-dealer goes bankrupt.” A fidelity bond protects the firm against employee dishonesty, not customers against the firm's bankruptcy (that is SIPC).","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-45","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"A registered person has purchased two tickets to attend a basketball game with a client. If the tickets cost $85 each, which of the following statements is NOT TRUE?","choices":{"A":"Under FINRA rules, this is considered entertainment.","B":"If the registered person did not attend the game and gave one of the tickets to the client, it is a violation.","C":"If the registered person did not attend the game and gave both of the tickets to the client, it is a violation.","D":"This doesn't require the approval of a principal of the firm."},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “If the registered person did not attend the game and gave one of the tickets to the client, it is a violation.” Entertainment (e.g., sports tickets) under $100 per person need not be pre-approved; giving tickets the RR does not use is not a violation.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-46","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following is TRUE if a mutual fund investor chooses to implement a systematic withdrawal plan from the fund?","choices":{"A":"The dividends and capital gains that are generated from the fund will be sufficient to make the payments.","B":"All payments will end on a specific date.","C":"The amount of each payment will remain the same.","D":"The withdrawals may result in a reduction of capital."},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “The withdrawals may result in a reduction of capital.” Systematic withdrawals can exceed income/distributions and erode the investor's principal over time.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-47","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"If a temporary hold has been placed on an account, it may be extended:","choices":{"A":"For 15 business days if the customer is still at risk of being exploited","B":"Once for 10 days, then again for 30 days, if customer is still at risk of being exploited","C":"Once for 30 days if the customer is still at risk of being exploited","D":"Once for 10 days if the customer is still at risk of being exploited"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Once for 10 days if the customer is still at risk of being exploited.” A temporary hold on a suspect account may be extended once for 10 business days if the customer is still at risk of financial exploitation.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-48","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"The SEC rules regarding record retention generally require that records be kept in an easily accessible location for the:","choices":{"A":"First two years","B":"First three years","C":"First six years","D":"Life of the firm"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “First two years.” SEC records-retention rules require books and records be kept readily accessible for the first two years.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-49","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The current yield on a municipal bond with a coupon rate of 4.50%, purchased at par and currently trading at $1,055, is:","choices":{"A":"4.15%","B":"4.26%","C":"4.46%","D":"4.50%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “4.26%.” Current yield = annual coupon ($45) / price ($1,055) = 4.26%.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-50","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"If an investor wants to receive immediate execution, he should enter a:","choices":{"A":"Market order","B":"Stop order","C":"Limit order","D":"Stop limit order"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Market order.” A market order seeks immediate execution at the best available price; limit/stop orders are not guaranteed to fill immediately.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-52","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"A previously registered person was convicted of a felony 14 years ago and has served out his sentence in federal prison. If he's now seeking employment as a registered representative, he should be informed that:","choices":{"A":"He may be hired as a registered representative","B":"He may not be hired as a registered representative","C":"He may be hired to provide investment advice to customers, but will not be permitted to receive compensation based on these transactions","D":"He may be hired to provide financial advice, but will not be permitted to become registered"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “He may be hired as a registered representative.” A felony conviction more than 10 years old does not bar registration, so the person may be hired as a registered representative.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-53","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"When interest rates are trending upward, the economy will normally be in which phase of the business cycle?","choices":{"A":"Expansion","B":"Contraction","C":"Trough","D":"Peak"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Expansion.” Rising interest rates typically occur during the expansion (growth) phase of the business cycle as demand for credit increases.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-54","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"Which of the following descriptions characterizes leveraged exchange-traded funds (ETFs)?","choices":{"A":"They are designed to deliver the same performance as an index or other benchmark","B":"They are designed to deliver a multiple of the performance of an index or other benchmark","C":"They are designed to deliver the opposite of the performance of an index or other benchmark","D":"They are designed to deliver a multiple of the opposite performance of an index or other benchmark"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “They are designed to deliver a multiple of the performance of an index or other benchmark.” Leveraged ETFs seek to deliver a multiple (e.g., 2x or 3x) of the daily return of their benchmark index.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-55","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"If a broker-dealer's trading desk purchases a large block of stock during the last minutes of trading in an effort to drive up the price, it is:","choices":{"A":"An acceptable practice that's referred to as a block trade","B":"An acceptable practice that's referred to as trading ahead","C":"A prohibited practice that's referred to as backing away","D":"A prohibited practice that's referred to as marking-the-close"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “A prohibited practice that's referred to as marking-the-close.” Buying at the close to push the price up is marking-the-close, a prohibited manipulative practice.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-56","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"A registered representative persuades a customer to purchase a security by assuring her that, should it fall in value, the representative will make up the difference in the account. This practice is:","choices":{"A":"Permitted if the arrangement is in writing and preapproved by the firm","B":"Permitted if the customer maintains an outside business relationship with the representative","C":"Permitted if the customer is an immediate family member","D":"Not permitted"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Not permitted.” A representative may not guarantee against loss or promise to make up declines in a customer's account - it is prohibited.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-57","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following statements is TRUE if interest rates rise?","choices":{"A":"Bond prices will rise, but bond fund prices will fall.","B":"Both bond and bond fund prices will rise.","C":"Both bond and bond fund prices will fall.","D":"Bond prices will fall, but bond fund prices will rise."},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “Both bond and bond fund prices will fall.” Bond and bond-fund prices both fall when interest rates rise, since their values move inversely to rates.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-58","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Which of the following events will have a positive effect on the U.S. balance of payments?","choices":{"A":"The government of China buying U.S. Treasury securities","B":"U.S. taxpayers paying taxes to the U.S. government","C":"Foreign investors selling U.S. equities and purchasing foreign securities","D":"U.S. corporations moving their headquarters to Europe"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “The government of China buying U.S. Treasury securities.” Foreign purchases of U.S. Treasury securities bring capital into the U.S., improving the U.S. balance of payments.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-59","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following is the likely result of persistent deflation?","choices":{"A":"A decrease in interest rates","B":"A decrease in the level of inflation","C":"A decrease in bond prices","D":"An increase in the value of equities"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “A decrease in interest rates.” Persistent deflation (falling prices) leads the central bank to lower interest rates to stimulate demand.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-60","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"A registered representative is sending an email to five clients. Which of the following statements is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"It is considered correspondence and subject to review by a principal.","B":"It is considered correspondence and subject to pre-approval by a principal.","C":"It is considered retail communication and subject to review by a principal.","D":"It is considered retail communication and subject to pre-approval by a principal."},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “It is considered correspondence and subject to review by a principal.” Email to five or fewer retail customers is correspondence, subject to post-use review by a principal (not prior approval).","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-61","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which of the following is classified as a joint account?","choices":{"A":"An account shared between two brothers.","B":"An account established under UGMA/UTMA.","C":"An account with third party trading authorization.","D":"A spousal IRA."},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “An account shared between two brothers.” A joint account is owned by two or more individuals, such as two brothers; UGMA and IRAs are not joint accounts.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-62","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which types of investments have historically shown a great deal of sensitivity to regulatory risk?","choices":{"A":"Limited partnerships","B":"Corporate bonds","C":"Common stocks","D":"Variable annuities"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Limited partnerships.” Limited partnerships (DPPs) are highly sensitive to regulatory and legislative risk affecting tax treatment and programs.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-63","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which of the following statements is TRUE concerning electronic communication networks (ECNs)?","choices":{"A":"They can be used only by retail investors.","B":"They can be used by investors who want to trade anonymously.","C":"They can be used only by institutional investors.","D":"They can be used by clients who don't want to use a broker-dealer."},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “They can be used by investors who want to trade anonymously.” ECNs let investors trade anonymously by matching orders electronically without revealing identity to the other side.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-64","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following statements BEST describes exchange-traded notes (ETNs)?","choices":{"A":"ETNs are debt instruments linked to the performance of a commodity, currency, or index","B":"ETNs are equity securities that pay a large dividend","C":"ETNs are mutual funds that invest in debt instruments","D":"ETNs are equity securities that represent ownership of a securities exchange"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “ETNs are debt instruments linked to the performance of a commodity, currency, or index.” ETNs are unsecured debt obligations whose return tracks a commodity, currency, or index; they are not equity.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-65","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"When a broker-dealer sells a security to a client and charges a commission on the transaction, it is acting as the client's:","choices":{"A":"Market maker","B":"Principal","C":"Designated market maker","D":"Agent"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Agent.” When a broker-dealer charges a commission, it acts as an agent on the customer's behalf, not as a principal.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-66","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"According to MSRB rules, the maximum gift that may be made to another person in relation to municipal activities is:","choices":{"A":"$50","B":"$150","C":"$100","D":"$200"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “$100.” MSRB limits gifts to $100 per person per year in connection with municipal securities business.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-67","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A stock that typically performs in parallel to the changes in the economy is referred to as a:","choices":{"A":"Cyclical stock","B":"Defensive stock","C":"Growth stock","D":"Value stock"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Cyclical stock.” Cyclical stocks rise and fall with the business/economic cycle; defensive stocks are less sensitive.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-68","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"In judging the fairness of a firm's markup, industry rules would NOT consider:","choices":{"A":"Whether the security was debt or equity","B":"The availability of the security in the market","C":"The pattern of markups","D":"Whether the client was a retail or institutional customer"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Whether the client was a retail or institutional customer.” Markup fairness depends on security type, availability, and the firm's markups, not on whether the client is retail or institutional.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-69","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"Final arbitration awards against registered representatives and/or firms are reported on which of the following forms?","choices":{"A":"Form U5","B":"Form U4","C":"Form U6","D":"Form BD"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “Form U6.” Final arbitration awards are reported on Form U6; Forms U4/U5 cover registration and termination, Form BD is for the firm.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-70","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which of the following transactions involving a registered representative (RR) is a violation of industry rules that FINRA established regarding private securities transactions?","choices":{"A":"An RR receiving income from speculative investments that are made in an outside brokerage account","B":"An RR splitting commissions with other registered representatives of the same broker-dealer","C":"An RR guaranteeing a customer from market losses through a promise to refund sales charges in an amount equal to the loss","D":"An RR selling securities in private transactions without the supervision and prior written consent of her employing broker-dealer"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “An RR selling securities in private transactions without the supervision and prior written consent of her employing broker-dealer.” Selling securities in private transactions without written notice and approval of the employing firm violates the private-securities-transactions rule.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-71","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following statements is TRUE concerning periodic payment variable annuities?","choices":{"A":"A client's number of annuity units never changes","B":"A client's number of accumulation units never changes","C":"Annuity contracts never have a beneficiary","D":"The monthly payout is fixed by the inflation index"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “A client's number of annuity units never changes.” In a periodic-payment variable annuity, accumulation units convert to a fixed number of annuity units at annuitization; those units never change.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-72","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A French company would like to have its stock traded in the U.S. securities markets. This would most likely be accomplished through the issuance of:","choices":{"A":"Euro call options","B":"Global Depository Receipts","C":"Eurodollar bonds","D":"American Depositary Receipts"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “American Depositary Receipts.” A foreign company lists in the U.S. via American Depositary Receipts (ADRs), created by a U.S. bank.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-73","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"A firm is the managing underwriter of a follow-on offering of a security that's listed on the NYSE. The aftermarket prospectus delivery rule:","choices":{"A":"Does not require the firm to deliver a prospectus","B":"Requires the firm to deliver a prospectus for 25 days","C":"Requires the firm to deliver a prospectus for 40 days","D":"Requires the firm to deliver a prospectus for 90 days"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “Does not require the firm to deliver a prospectus.” Once a security is listed (NYSE), follow-on offerings are exempt from the prospectus delivery requirement for secondary-market trades.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-74","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"During a period of stable interest rates, which type of preferred stock tends to be the most volatile?","choices":{"A":"Non-cumulative","B":"Cumulative","C":"Participating","D":"Convertible"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Convertible.” Convertible preferred tracks the underlying common stock once in-the-money, making it the most volatile in a stable-rate environment.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-75","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"All of the following persons are permitted to be named as a trusted contact person for a senior investor, EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"A family member","B":"A business associate","C":"A law firm","D":"A friend"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “A law firm.” A trusted contact person may be a family member, friend, or business associate, but not a law firm representing the customer.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-76","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"If a customer exceeds SIPC limits:","choices":{"A":"The customer will receive cash rather than his securities","B":"The customer is a secured creditor","C":"The customer doesn't have a claim to the excess amount","D":"The customer is a general creditor"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “The customer is a general creditor.” SIPC covers up to its limits; amounts above SIPC protection make the customer a general (unsecured) creditor of the firm.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-77","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Who keeps track of the shareholders of a mutual fund?","choices":{"A":"The custodian bank","B":"The transfer agent","C":"The investment adviser","D":"The underwriter"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “The transfer agent.” The transfer agent maintains the record of mutual fund shareholders (ownership, account balances).","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-78","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"A registered representative previously operated a sole proprietorship and requested protection from bankruptcy. The representative did not disclose her affiliation with the proprietorship when she filed Form U4. Which of the following statements regarding the application is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"The registered representative must update her Form U4 within 120 days.","B":"The registered representative has filed a statement with false or misleading statements.","C":"Bankruptcies are not a disclosure item on Form U4.","D":"If the firm's compliance department signed the Form U4, then no changes are required."},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “The registered representative has filed a statement with false or misleading statements.” Omitting a required disclosure (the proprietorship/bankruptcy) makes the Form U4 statement false or misleading.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-79","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"An equity inverse exchange-traded fund (ETF) is most similar to:","choices":{"A":"A real estate investment trust (REIT)","B":"Buying on margin","C":"An equity mutual fund","D":"Selling stock short"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Selling stock short.” An inverse (bear) ETF profits when the market falls, functioning like a short stock position.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-80","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Who is responsible for creating the official statement for a municipal bond offering?","choices":{"A":"The issuer","B":"Bond counsel for the issuer","C":"The underwriting syndicate","D":"Bond counsel for the underwriting syndicate"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct choice (A) is: “The issuer.” The municipal issuer prepares the official statement; bond counsel provides the legal opinion.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-81","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A company wants to buy back some of its shares from existing shareholders through a tender offer. The company offers to buy up to a maximum of 5 million shares at $15 per share, but sets no minimum number of shares to purchase. A shareholder wants to sell 3,000 shares. If 4.9 million shares have been tendered, how many of the investor's shares will the company buy?","choices":{"A":"45,000","B":"0","C":"2,940","D":"3,000"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “3,000.” With no minimum and 4.9M tendered against a 5M max, the offer is prorated (98%), so the 3,000 shares tender at 2,940 shares bought.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-82","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which of the following persons can a registered representative either make a loan to or borrow money from without providing notification to her employer?","choices":{"A":"Another employee of an affiliated broker-dealer","B":"An institution that's in the business of borrowing or lending funds","C":"An individual with whom the RR maintains a personal relationship","D":"A company with which the RR has a business relationship"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “An institution that's in the business of borrowing or lending funds.” An RR may borrow from or lend to a bank or other institution in the business of lending without notifying the employer; loans to individuals require notice.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-83","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A corporation will be paying a cash dividend to its shareholders. On what date will the market price of the stock be reduced?","choices":{"A":"Declared date","B":"Ex-date","C":"Meeting date","D":"Payment date"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct choice (B) is: “Ex-date.” The stock price is reduced on the ex-dividend date to reflect the dividend no longer attached.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-84","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"A full-service broker-dealer is required to conduct a test of its anti-money laundering procedures at least:","choices":{"A":"Monthly","B":"Quarterly","C":"Annually","D":"Daily"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct choice (C) is: “Annually.” FINRA requires broker-dealers to test their AML program at least annually.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"},{"id":"yt-guru6-85","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following choices would NOT be subject to the holding period restriction under Rule 144?","choices":{"A":"Restricted stock acquired under an investment letter","B":"Restricted stock acquired under a stock option plan","C":"Control stock acquired under a private placement","D":"Control stock acquired through an open-market purchase"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The correct choice (D) is: “Control stock acquired through an open-market purchase.” Control stock bought in the open market has no Rule 144 holding-period requirement; restricted and privately placed control stock do.","source":"YouTube: Series 7 Guru (guru6)"}];
